The paper deals with the analysis of a local search algorithm for solving the satisfiability (SAT) problem, which is a well-known problem in artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also introduces a new concept called the backbone of a SAT instance, which is related to the structure of the problem instance and its solution space. This concept is relevant to the fields of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS), computational complexity (cs.CC), and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper uses statistical analysis to study the behavior of the local search algorithm on different types of SAT instances, which is a topic in data mining (cs.DM).
